HEADWORD: madras
<hw>ma*dras"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So named after
<etsep>Madras</etsep>, a city and presidency of India.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A large silk-and-cotton kerchief, usually of bright
colors, such as those often used by negroes for turbans.</def></p>

<p><q>A black woman in blue cotton gown, red-and-yellow
<qex>madras</qex> turban . . . crouched against the wall.</q>
<rj><qau>G. W. Cable.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A light patterned cotton fabric.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Madreperl</ent>⟦br⟧
